Summary: The document reports on the toxicity and immune response of two types of gold nanoparticles (Au25 NCs) in mice. The nanoparticles were coated with either glutathione (GSH) or bovine serum albumin (BSA) and were administered to mice for 24 hours or 28 days. The results show that both types of nanoparticles did not cause significant changes in body weight, clinical signs, or behaviors in the mice. Histopathological examination of organs did not reveal any macroscopic changes, except for the liver in the BSA-coated nanoparticles. The immune response was also investigated, showing that the thymus index increased significantly in mice treated with GSH-coated nanoparticles, while the spleen index remained unchanged. Hematology and biochemistry tests were also conducted, revealing no significant changes in most parameters, except for slight increases in liver enzymes in mice treated with BSA-coated nanoparticles. Overall, the study suggests that both types of Au25 NCs are relatively safe and non-toxic in mice.
